<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-490-871  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 490 871.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Data Communications  Sept 21 1990 v19 n12 p55(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fiber optics in the '90s: fact and fiction.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Head, Joe.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Although fiber optics technology used in networks has grown inpopularity, misconceptions abound.andP;  Many network designers makethe assumption that fiber optics is only cost-effective forhigh-capacity applications, since it can transmit data at100M-bits or more.andP;  However, trying to conserve fiber is not a wayto save money.andP;  In addition, network managers need to consider theeffects of a 256-channel concentrator's failure compared with a32-channel's failure using a dedicated fiber pair.andP;  It is lessexpensive to burn a pair of fibers in new applications than tooverprotect the entire system.andP;  Another fact to remember is thatsignal quality, diagnostics and reliability on fiber trunks arefar better than copper connections at competitive prices.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Network ManagementBusiness PlanningCostComparisonCablesFiber opticsOutlookFuture of Computing.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphtable.andO;Caption:   Falling FDDI: the cost of interface cards. (graph)Cable losses at typical LAN distances. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>